Sydney is known for its beautiful and deep harbour. However, nestled in the heart of southern end of #bluemountains is a water body 4 times larger than the harbour. One of Sydney’s life systems and best kept secret, Warragamba Dam.
Built as part of nation building after the #ww2 men and women from around the world came to build one of the world’s biggest dams. It took 12 years to build this massive structure with turbines making the long journey from #southhampton to #sydney...
Lake Burragorang formed by the dam holds and supplies water to all us Sydneysiders and is a stunning sight to behold (pics 1-2).
The drought since 2013 led to the alarmingly low water levels and the dam usually known to flood had reached the end of its tether by the summer of 2020. 
Of course we have been blessed with rains now and the dam and the lake are back to their shimmering capacity.
An hours drive south west of Sydney, the #warragamba area has an interesting history, heritage and beautiful lookouts... a perfect Saturday out and about knowing more about Sydney and surrounds....

node.text: I believe as you also have your pros and cons but at some moments your cons weighs heavier than those pros we are thankful for. Having said that, we all know you were a byproduct of a virus but now we just want to eradicate you from our life. We want our freedom and most importantly we just want our life back.

To the new quarantine life,
 There comes a time when everything seems to be going fine but a mini apocalypse kind of unexpected thing just appears out of no where, yes you were that apocalypse for everyone all around the world
  You were like an Indian relative who would show up without giving any prior notice. Although, we were aware that there will be a comma which is going to arrive in our lives but we didn't expect it to be such a long pause. You did become an unnecessary pause of our beautiful song called "life"
 At the beginning, it didn't seem to be this major issue instead we were hoping to enjoy those few days of leisure and get an escape from all the hustle. But life doesn't move as you want it to, so all the plans and enjoyment were doomed by your presence. We couldn't be able to do what we wanted, we wanted to live but you forced us to turn on the survival mode, more than a master of our own self we became a slave of your existence.
 The pressure was building on each one of us to try and get back to the normal but you made us realise that there won't be any normal, atleast for now or maybe ever. Now your presence has began to haunt people, some couldn't get bread while others are still on the survival mode. 
  There has been a lot of hatred for you, but just looking at that moonlight amidst those dark clouds helped me understand that maybe just for a mere instance some of your perks are somewhat a blessing in disguise. I know everything went from bright to dull in these past few months but you made us realise that there is something which is more important than those rush of life and that is our family and friends. You made us perceive the fact that there presence is of the utmost importance in our life, you enlarged everything in life for us and made us believe that all those things we were directly or indirectly taking for granted is an absolute luxury for us and we can't thank you enough for that. By pushing us at the end of the darkness you made us look at the brighter side of few things

In this video I talk about post lockdown reflections, and how we have all practiced compassion without knowing it⁣
⁣
üåü Compassion is such an important part of my life, and of everyone's life in some way or another. We as humans can feel what others feel just by imagining it, just by watching a movie, that emotional trigger is set off⁣
⁣
üåü There is a deeper part of us which wants to know that the other person is okay, and that we are okay. But sometimes it's forgotten through greed, jealously, inadequacy, hatred, rage.⁣
⁣
üåü These can consume us and make us sick more than the corona virus, because its an ongoing sickness. Once you let compassion flood your system, and look at the world from this point of view. You will have direct positive.physiological changes, yes it's been shown in studies!⁣
⁣
üåü You literally become better when put yourself in someone's shoes, and when you deeply feel their pain and their joy.⁣
⁣
üåü We have all practiced compassion over lockdown in one way or another, sharing the burden, sharing how our experiences have gone, staying safe, nobody escaped lockdown and we were all in this together. No race, no country, no nothing was there to separate us. We had something in common with everyone⁣
⁣
üåü As you ease out of lockdown, remind yourself of this something in common that you have with humanity, and take your compassion into everything you do. Try it for a week, the next time you feel enraged that someone is attacking you, ask yourself where in that person it's coming from, now how do you feel?⁣
⁣
üöÄ Let me know how your life changes in this week. And let me know how this video may have impacted you by sending me a message. I'd happily share some positive vibes with you and celebrate your successes with you! üôèüèΩ

Don't we live to do what we love? Do you know what interests you? What do you love to do in free time? 

Simply think? Or paint? Or sketch? Or play video games? Or talk to pets? Or dance? Or read? Or simply scrolling? 

We all have that one thing in our heart we love and we wish to do! Then why don't we explore creativity in turning what we love into something which can take form of a survival skill in our life..!? 

In conversation with Preeti from @khushi.delight we are reflecting upon the activities we really love to do and how one can shape it into something meaningful. Preeti loves to paint, professionally she has been a graphic designer and a teacher, but due to lockdown she is home, but she is happy to have had plenty time to relish her love for painting. 

Preeti welcomes you to check her paintings and artwork on her channel @khushi.delight

As mosques üïå were closed and still are for communal social events, connecting with people over the web instead of face to face has been a blessing. Covid is NOT going to keep colour out of our lives!
Splash, an annual art competition for children with special needs has been hosted by Concern India Foundation in different cities for many years. We saw no reason for Covid to change that! A virtual version of Splash was hosted by our Hyderabad branch on 13th August and it rocked! 17 children participated from the safe environs of the shelter-home for special children, while a number of others participated from their own homes. The theme of the contest was Health & Hygiene and the children came up with some interesting creations which were photographed and mailed to us. Concern India Foundation volunteers were virtually present to encourage the children and candies were sent to all participants. Thank you to our sponsor @cotiviti for making this possible and giving the children a day to remember!

Have you ever had these kind off mood swings where you are irritated for no reason, just bad feelings, too bored and you are procrastinating too much on what you want to do - when u have a lot to do, and stressing on unavoidable side of your lockdown days !? I was feeling all of these in the last days. 

But when this happens, something that has always worked for me is - to make a small change in life. Very small. It can even be dragging a small cute pencil from a store and playing with it. 

And this time - I changed the light in my room, I decor my room with these fairy lights around my vision board and trust me, I am spending my evening so fresh and beautiful. 

A small change can really bring a big difference in your life.  Mind your mind - Your thoughts drive how you feel. How you feel drive your action. AND RELAX !! Don’t let yourself down in these phases of life. 

Do you have these kind of mood swings ever? Let me know what you guys do !! #bettertogether

I often want words to knit themselves in such a pleasant display that I wouldn’t have to try so hard to hide, behind the bland pleasantness of so much of human. Pleasantness like luke warm tea in a chipped cup, sitting on a tattered sofa, feeling stale breath of the other on your skin, with a smile like a bandaid on years old wound- yes; I’m fine,  everything is usual. 

Shouldn’t it be worrying that everything is usual?

I have lighting phosphorus in veins, and slithering giant gnomes in heart, earthquake in my brain, and words crawling on my tongue causing fissures, spurting like a bottle of soda, if only you would listen beyond usual. 

We can talk of how I hate creases in bed and do nothing to remove them, or how read (v) as (iv) twice today- and wondered  how and why do I do that. I ll tell you what I think of Tuesdays. How it lacks character and is likely to agree with both right wing and left wing, how Tuesday would agree with a bigot, and a secular, a sexist and a feminist. Tuesday is half boomer, half millennial- hopping from promise of Monday with hope and dread like of Election Day, and then moving to business like demeanor of capitalist Wednesday- putting us all in assembly line, labeling us with Usual. #notusual #mentalpeas #diaryofarandomgirl #srishtiwrites #scribbler #lockdowndiaries #hindsightis2020

The art of renovation
.
.
.
We get caught up moving on with our daily lives so much that we often tend to forget about things which excited us when we bought it home the first time.
.
.
Or may be because our brain had started to ignore it, kind of like¬†Troxler effect¬†applied on the things which have become part of our daily life.
.
.
.
And on top of it, we only see what we want to see. For instance, my mother always sees how much chaotic my house is every time she visits, but I only see the order within the chaos. [Note: I have a toddler-teenager and a husband, my house is allowed to be chaotic]
.
.
For some reason I love buddha statues! [No, I don't share any traits with him, especially patience] Maybe its because he looks so calm in any posture. Or maybe because I think he sleeps all the time which is one of my favourite activity anywhere.
.
.
.
Out of the few ideas which I had for this statue, I decided to settle with painting it simple.
.
.
I wanted to do a contrast colour for the head part. I wanted to highlight those curls and the high bun. So decided to go for a bold gold colour.
.
.

Jayachandran is a Lecturer at Center for Exact Humanities, IIIT, Hyderabad. With an Electronics Engineering background, Jayachandran started his career as a Software Engineer with Wipro. 
He joined Kalakshetra Foundation as a part of Research and Documentation Department, later served as Asst.Professor at Kalakshetra.

Jayachandran started Bharatanatyam training under Smt.Meera Narayanan and Sri.Gopinathan. Later his dancing skills were refined by Smt.Leela Samson, Prof.C.V.Chandrashekar and Smt.Jaya Chandrashekar and Smt.Bragha Bessell. 
He did Diploma in Saiva Siddhanta, B.A. History, M.A. History, M.A Philosophy and M.A. Bharatanatyam.  His paper ‘Tiruvarur sthalam as interpreted in Smt.Rukmini Devi’s choreography’ has won him the best lecture-demonstration award from the Music Academy.

The Rattan Pillow Duster
Klaus Aalto is one half of the Helsinki based design studio Aalto + Aalto submits the rattan pillow duster for life with objects.

I’ve always been keen on traditional everyday life objects. They normally have developed themselves to their final form according to usability and a tender sense of aesthetics. They are not designed by anyone but rather a communal creation in a long timeline. The rattan pillow duster is an inspiring example of this – Klaus Aalto

shortcode_media.accessibility_caption: Photo by @lifewithobjects in Helsinki, Finnland with @aaltoxaalto. Image may contain: text that says 'Aalto+Aalto +Aalto'.

node.text: Aalto+Aalto is a Helsinki-based design office working with products, spaces and exhibitions. Their aim is to create special everyday objects with a strong identity and story. They are inspired by time-tested old techniques, all kinds of factories and flea markets. Their special skill is managing to make things which are imaginative and different but still simple and timeless. Their work has been widely exhibited, is included in the collections of the Design museum in Helsinki and in Quebec and has been awarded the iF golden product design award. Aalto+Aalto are Elina Aalto and Klaus Aalto

OOPS ü§¶üèΩ‍‚ôÄÔ∏è I put the caramelized banana on top when it was still warm so it melted the top layer üòÖ

My alterations ü•£
1. The reviews all said the layer of banana between the ice cream and the crust made it super hard to cut so I opted for bananas on top instead! 
2. Replaced the layer of banana with a layer of chocolate to keep the crust crunchy! Check out fun facts for why ü§î

Tips and Tricks üßë‍üç≥
1. Allow each layer of ice cream to complete freeze before adding the next layer to avoid flavours mixing! We waited WAY longer than the 20 minutes called for - closer to 2 hours!
2. A silicon cake pan is perfect to use as it makes the pie so easy to remove! 

Fun fact üéÅ
As a Food Scientist one of my most memorable classes was the one where we learned about chocolate coating on the inside of ice cream cones sold ready to eat (like Drumsticks or Cornetto)üç¶. The coating is fat-based so forms a barrier that stops the moisture from the ice cream moving to the cone and making it soggy. It's essential to a good Drumstick or Cornetto. Those that first put them on the market spent tons of time and money on scientists üë©‍üî¨ to figure out a way to not let the chocolate pool at the bottom of the cone, only to find out after they did that people actually love the chocolate ends! üòÖ
